glish (of Norman origin): variant of   Turberville  . This form of the surname is very rare in Britain and Ireland."],"variants":[{"name":"Turberville","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name, probably from Thouberville (Eure), or possibly from Trubleville (Seine-Maritime), both in France. The two may have been confused in surname usage."]}]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Verch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Orlo.","German: variant of   Ferch  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ferch","meanings":["German: variant of   Ferg  . Compare   Verch  .","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förtsch</b> (see   Foertsch  ).","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förch</b> (see   Foerch  )."]}]},{"name":"Adam","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical.  See  <b>Adam</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Maud Verch Adam Tuberville was born about 1427, in England, United Kingdom, her father, Adam Turberville ap Hywel, was 27 and her mother, Unknown ferch Gruffudd, was 36. She had at least 2 sons with Sir William Herbert 1st Earl of Pembroke. She died in 1460, in Abergavenny, Monmouthshire, Wales, at the age of 34."},"et":{"about 1427–1460":"umbes 1427–1460","1427–1460":"1427–1460","–Male":"Surnud","1423–1469":"1423–1469","1442–1510":"1442–1510","1444–1504":"1444–1504","1401–Male":"1401–Surnud","1392–1454":"1392–1454","1460":"1460","Abt 1444":"umbes 1444","1392":"1392","1469":"1469","1401":"1401","1423":"1423","1444":"1444","1510":"1510","about 1427":"umbes 1427","1454":"1454","1442":"1442","1504":"1504","1427":"1427","Llanfyhangel, Abergavenny, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Abergavenny, Monmouthshire, Wales","Abergavenny, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Abergavenny, Monmouthshire, Wales","Monmouthshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Monmouthshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Lianfair Cilgedin, Abergavenny, Monmouthsire, Wales":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Raglan, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Raglan, Monmouthshire, Wales"},"fi":{"about 1427–1460":"noin 1427–1460","1427–1460":"1427–1460","–Male":"Kuollut","1423–1469":"1423–1469","1442–1510":"1442–1510","1444–1504":"1444–1504","1401–Male":"1401–Kuollut","1392–1454":"1392–1454","1460":"1460","Abt 1444":"noin 1444","1392":"1392","1469":"1469","1401":"1401","1423":"1423","1444":"1444","1510":"1510","about 1427":"noin 1427","1454":"1454","1442":"1442","1504":"1504","1427":"1427","Llanfyhangel, Abergavenny, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Abergavenny, Monmouthshire, Wales","Abergavenny, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Abergavenny, Monmouthshire, Wales","Monmouthshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Monmouthshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Lianfair Cilgedin, Abergavenny, Monmouthsire, Wales":"Englanti, Yhd